      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Campaign Blahs</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Keith Burt letter comments on July 24 editorial appraising 2000 presidential campaign at midsummer</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Campaign at Midsummer'' (editorial, July 24):</p>
        <p>You say ''already it has become the campaign that people like to complain about.'' In fact, the most widespread (if not vocal) complaint about the 2000 campaign is dissatisfaction with both parties because of the corrupting influence of special-interest money.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Campaign at Midsummer'' (editorial, July 24):</p>
        <p>You say ''already it has become the campaign that people like to complain about.'' In fact, the most widespread (if not vocal) complaint about the 2000 campaign is dissatisfaction with both parties because of the corrupting influence of special-interest money.</p>
        <p>Many Americans now admit that they won't even watch the conventions; instead, more attention is starting to come to both the activist demonstrations being planned and the ''shadow conventions'' (focusing on issues that the major candidates have ignored: money politics, wealth inequality and the failed ''war on drugs'').</p>
        <p>Perhaps these alternative events will help reverse the most disturbing trend in American politics: low voter turnout.</p>
        <p>KEITH BURT  Cambridge, Mass., July 25, 2000</p>
      </block>
